model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "POE_WORKS_VOLUME_1_001",
  "condition": "simplify",
  "rewritten_text": "When we judge an author's merit and decide where to place him among our literary icons, we have the right to view him from our own perspective and measure him by our own standards. However, when we estimate the power displayed in his work, we must be guided by his own intentions, comparing his results to his own ideals to see what might be missing. We differ from Mr. Poe regarding the purpose of art. He believes its goal is the creation of Beauty, and perhaps we only disagree on the definition of that word. Regardless, in our discussion of his writing, we will use his own standards as our guide. The temple of poetry is accessible from every side, and there is plenty of room for everyone who brings offerings or seeks guidance.\n\nIn his stories, Mr. Poe chooses to demonstrate his power primarily in that dim region stretching from the outer limits of the probable into the strange territory of superstition and unreality. He remarkably combines two faculties rarely found together: the ability to influence a reader's mind through the subtle shadows of mystery, and a precision of detail that ignores nothing, not even a pin or a button. Both are natural results of his mind's dominant quality, which we have mentioned before: analysis. This is what distinguishes the artist. His mind immediately looks toward the intended effect. Having decided to evoke specific emotions in the reader, he ensures all smaller parts contribute strictly to that central goal. Even his mystery is mathematical to him. To him, X is always a known quantity. In any picture he paints, he understands the chemical properties of all his colors. No matter how vague his figures may seem or how formless his shadows, the outline is as clear and distinct to him as a geometric diagram. For this reason, Mr. Poe has no sympathy for Mysticism. The Mystic lives within the mystery, surrounded by it; it colors all his thoughts and affects his vision, giving even common objects a rainbow-like edge. Mr. Poe, conversely, is an outside observer. He analyzes, dissects, and watches with a calm eye the very pulse of the machine, for that is what it essentially is to him: a collection of wheels, cogs, and pistons all working to produce a specific result.\n\nThis analytical tendency balances his poetic side, and by giving him the patience to be precise, it allows him to inject a wonderful sense of reality into his most unreal fantasies. He depicts monomania with great power. He loves to dissect these mental cancers and trace the subtle branches of their roots. He also has strange success in raising images of horror, sometimes conveying a terrible doubt through a dark hint, which is the secret of all horror. He leaves the task of finishing the picture to the imagination, the only thing capable of doing so. For much imaginary work was there; Conceit deceitful, so compact, so kind, That for Achilles’ image stood his spear Grasped in an armed hand; himself behind Was left unseen, save to the eye of mind."
}

