model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "POE_WORKS_VOLUME_1_003",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "After roughly four and a half hours, the balloon reached a sufficient state of inflation. I proceeded to fasten the car and stowed my equipment inside, making sure to include the condensing device, a generous amount of water, and a substantial store of provisions like pemmican, which offers high nutritional value in a compact form. I also brought along a cat and two pigeons. With dawn approaching, I decided it was time to leave. I dropped a lit cigar as if by mistake, and while stooping to retrieve it, I secretly lit the slow match that extended slightly from the bottom edge of one of the smaller barrels. The three creditors failed to notice this action; I leaped into the car, severed the lone rope tethering me to the ground, and was gratified to ascend rapidly, easily lifting one hundred and seventy-five pounds of lead ballast with the capacity to carry even more.\n\nHowever, I had barely reached an altitude of fifty yards when a deafening, chaotic storm of fire, smoke, sulfur, limbs, gravel, burning timber, and molten metal roared upward after me. My heart failed me, and I collapsed into the base of the car, shaking with absolute terror. I realized then that I had severely miscalculated, and the primary effects of the blast were still to come. Within a second, I felt blood surge to my head, followed immediately by a blast I will never forget, which shattered the night and seemed to tear the sky apart. Upon later reflection, I correctly identified the intensity of the explosion as a result of my position directly above the epicenter. At that moment, though, my only thought was survival. The balloon first buckled, then expanded violently, spun with dizzying speed, and finally, swaying like a drunkard, threw me over the edge of the car. I was left hanging at a terrifying height, head down and facing outward, suspended by a thin three-foot cord that had slipped through a gap in the wicker and caught my left foot as I tumbled. It is truly impossible to convey the horror of that moment. I struggled for air, my body racked by a shivering fit like an ague, my eyes feeling as though they were popping from their sockets, and a wave of nausea overcame me until I finally lost consciousness.\n\nI cannot say how long I remained in that state. It must have been quite a while, for when I regained a partial sense of awareness, dawn was breaking, the balloon was at a massive altitude above an endless expanse of ocean, and there was no sign of land anywhere across the vast horizon."
}

