eld by a thin, three-foot cord that had accidentally hung through a gap in the wickerwork and in which my left foot had fortunately become tangled as I fell. It is impossible—utterly impossible—to convey the horror of my situation. I gasped for air, a shudder like a feverish chill shook every nerve and muscle in my body, my eyes felt as if they were popping from their sockets, a sickening nausea overwhelmed me, and finally, I passed out.\n\nI cannot say how long I remained in that state. It must have been quite a while, because when I partially regained consciousness, I found day was breaking, the balloon was at a massive altitude over a vast ocean, and there was not a trace of land to be seen anywhere within the limits of the horizon."
