  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "Having embraced this perspective, I felt minimal hesitation. Assuming that my journey would encounter an atmosphere fundamentally identical to that at the earth's surface, I believed that M. Grimm’s highly clever device would easily allow me to compress enough of it for breathing. This would eliminate the primary barrier to a lunar voyage. I had certainly invested significant funds and effort into modifying the equipment for this purpose, and I anticipated its successful use, provided I could finish the trip in a sensible timeframe. This returns me to the question of potential travel speed.\n\nIt is a fact that balloons, during the initial phase of their departure from the ground, are known to ascend at a relatively modest speed. Now, the lifting force depends entirely on the gas inside the balloon being lighter than the surrounding air; and, at first glance, it does not seem likely that, as the balloon gains height and enters atmospheric layers of rapidly decreasing density—I mean, it does not seem logical that, during this upward movement, the initial speed would increase. Conversely, I was unaware of any documented flight where a decrease in the actual rate of ascent was noted; although that should have occurred, if only due to gas leaking from poorly made balloons coated with inferior varnish. It appeared, therefore, that the impact of such leakage merely offset the influence of some accelerating force. I concluded that, assuming I encountered the medium I had envisioned, and assuming it proved to be essentially what we call atmospheric air, it would matter little at what level of thinness I found it—that is, regarding my ability to rise—because the gas within the balloon would not only undergo a somewhat similar thinning (which would allow me to release enough to prevent bursting), but, being what it was, would in any case remain lighter than any mixture of nitrogen and oxygen. Meanwhile, the pull of gravity would steadily decrease according to the inverse square of the distance, and thus, with a vastly increasing speed, I would eventually reach those remote regions where the earth's gravitational pull is replaced by that of the moon. Based on these thoughts, I did not deem it necessary to burden myself with more supplies than would suffice for forty days.\n\nThere remained, however, another obstacle that caused me some minor anxiety. It has been noted that, during balloon flights to significant heights, in addition to the difficulty of breathing, intense discomfort is felt in the head and body, frequently accompanied by nosebleeds and other distressing symptoms, which become increasingly troublesome as the altitude increases."
}

