  "rewritten_text": "Having adopted this view of the subject, I had little further hesitation. Assuming that I would encounter an atmosphere similar to that at the earth's surface during my journey, I believed that M. Grimm’s ingenious device would easily allow me to condense enough air for breathing. This would remove the main obstacle to a trip to the moon. I had spent significant money and effort adapting the equipment for this purpose, and I felt confident it would work if I could finish the voyage within a reasonable time. This brings me back to the question of how fast I could travel.\n\nIt is true that balloons usually rise at a moderate speed when they first leave the earth. The power of ascent comes entirely from the gas in the balloon being lighter than the surrounding air. At first glance, it does not seem likely that the balloon’s speed would increase as it rises into thinner layers of the atmosphere. On the other hand, I was not aware of any recorded flight where the rate of ascent actually slowed down, even though that should have happened—if only because gas leaks from poorly constructed balloons sealed with ordinary varnish. It seemed, therefore, that the effect of such leaks was only enough to cancel out some accelerating force. I concluded that if I found the medium I expected, and if it proved to be essentially atmospheric air, it would make little difference how thin it was regarding my ability to ascend. The gas in the balloon would be subject to similar thinning, and I could release enough to prevent an explosion. Regardless, it would remain lighter than any mixture of nitrogen and oxygen. Meanwhile, the force of gravity would constantly decrease in proportion to the square of the distance. Consequently, I would eventually reach those distant regions where the earth’s pull is replaced by the moon’s, traveling at a tremendously increasing speed. Based on these ideas, I did not think it necessary to carry more than forty days' worth of supplies.\n\nThere was still one other difficulty, however, that caused me some concern. It has been noted that during balloon flights to significant heights, travelers experience not only difficulty breathing but also great discomfort in the head and body. This is often accompanied by nosebleeds and other alarming symptoms, which become increasingly severe as the altitude rises."
}

