{
  "passage_id": "POE_WORKS_VOLUME_1_005",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "After repeating this process several times, the room was finally filled with air suitable for breathing. However, in such a restricted area, the air would quickly grow stale and unusable due to constant inhalation. It was then expelled through a minor valve located at the base of the car, as the heavy air naturally descended into the lighter atmosphere underneath. To prevent the discomfort of creating a complete vacuum inside the chamber, this cleaning process was performed incrementally rather than all at once; the valve was opened briefly and then shut, until a few pump strokes from the condenser replaced the expelled air. For experimental purposes, I placed the cat and her kittens in a small basket, hanging it outside the car from a button near the valve, which allowed me to feed them whenever required. I performed this with some danger, reaching beneath the car with one of the previously mentioned poles equipped with a hook before sealing the chamber entrance.\n\n“By the time I finished these preparations and filled the chamber as described, it was nearly nine o’clock. Throughout the time I spent on these tasks, I suffered extreme agony from breathing difficulties, and I deeply regretted the carelessness, or perhaps recklessness, of delaying such a vital task until the final moment. Yet, having finally succeeded, I quickly began to enjoy the rewards of my creation. I was breathing with total ease once more—and indeed, why should I not? I was also pleasantly surprised to discover that the intense pains that had plagued me were largely gone. A mild headache, along with a feeling of tightness or swelling in my wrists, ankles, and throat, was almost all that remained. It seemed clear that most of the discomfort caused by the loss of atmospheric pressure had faded, as I had anticipated, and that much of the suffering from the previous two hours should have been blamed entirely on inadequate respiration.\n\n“At twenty minutes to nine—shortly before I sealed the chamber—the mercury reached its lowest point in the barometer, which, as I noted earlier, was of a specialized, extended design. It showed that I had reached an altitude of 132,000 feet, or twenty-five miles, allowing me to observe a portion of the earth’s surface equal to one three-hundred-and-twentieth of its total area. By nine o’clock, I had lost sight of the land to the east, but not before noticing that the balloon was moving swiftly toward the north-northwest. The curve of the ocean below was clearly visible, though my sight was frequently blocked by drifting cloud formations."
}

