estow it upon me, I need only use it properly to reach the gold it points to. Jupiter, bring me that scarab!\" \"What! The bug, master? I’d rather not trouble that bug—you must get it yourself.\" Legrand then stood up with a grave, stately air and brought me the beetle from a glass case. It was a beautiful scarab, unknown to naturalists at the time—a significant scientific prize. There were two round, black spots near one end of its back and a long one near the other. The scales were exceptionally hard and glossy, appearing exactly like burnished gold. The insect’s weight was remarkable, and, considering everything, I could hardly blame Jupiter for his opinion; however, I could not for the life of me understand why Legrand agreed with him."
