  "rewritten_text": "We now continue with the record, as copied by Mr. Forsyth from the combined manuscripts of Mr. Monck Mason and Mr. Ainsworth. The main text is written by Mr. Mason, while a postscript is added daily by Mr. Ainsworth, who is currently drafting a more detailed and surely captivating report of the journey for future publication.\n\n“THE JOURNAL.\n\n“Saturday, April 6th.—Having completed all necessary preparations the previous evening, we began inflating the balloon at dawn. However, a dense fog clung to the silk, making it difficult to handle and delaying our progress until nearly eleven o’clock. We then cast off in high spirits, rising slowly and consistently on a gentle northerly breeze that carried us toward the British Channel. The lift was stronger than anticipated, and as we climbed above the cliffs into the sunlight, our ascent accelerated. Wishing to conserve gas early in the trip, I decided to continue climbing for the time being. We soon extended our guide-rope, but even after it cleared the ground, we kept rising quickly. The balloon remained remarkably stable and appeared magnificent. Ten minutes after departure, the barometer showed an altitude of 15,000 feet. The weather was excellent, and the sight of the landscape below—always romantic—was particularly majestic. Thick vapors filled the deep ravines, making them look like lakes, while the crags and peaks to the southeast were jumbled together like the mythical cities of the East. We were nearing the southern mountains, but our height was more than enough to clear them safely. We soared over the peaks shortly after, and Mr. Ainsworth and the sailors were struck by how low the mountains seemed from the car; great altitude in a balloon tends to flatten the terrain below into a nearly uniform surface. By half-past eleven, still traveling mostly south, we caught our first glimpse of the Bristol Channel, and fifteen minutes later, the coastal surf appeared directly under us as we moved out over the water. We decided to release enough gas to lower our guide-rope and its attached buoys into the sea. This was done at once, and we began a slow descent. Within twenty minutes, the first buoy touched the water, and after the second followed shortly after, our altitude stabilized. Eager to evaluate the rudder and screw, we immediately engaged both to shift our heading eastward toward Paris. The rudder allowed us to change direction instantly, positioning us nearly perpendicular to the wind; we then activated the screw’s spring and were pleased to see it drive us forward as intended."
}

