  "rewritten_text": "It is recalled that, in the standard telling of these stories, a certain king, having legitimate reason to distrust his queen, not only executes her but swears an oath, by his beard and the prophet, to marry the most attractive young woman in his realm each evening, only to hand her over to the headsman the following dawn. Having carried out this oath for many years with a religious precision and consistency that reflected well upon his piety and sound judgment, he was disturbed one afternoon—presumably while praying—by a visit from his grand vizier, whose daughter had conceived a plan. Her name was Scheherazade, and her intention was to either save the country from this tax on its beauty or die, as is customary for heroines, in the effort. Consequently, even though it was not a leap year—which adds to the merit of her sacrifice—she instructed her father, the grand vizier, to propose her hand to the king. The king readily accepted this offer—he had intended to take her anyway, having delayed only out of apprehension toward the vizier—but in doing so, he made it perfectly clear to everyone that, regardless of the vizier’s status, he had no intention of abandoning any part of his vow or his royal rights. Therefore, when the lovely Scheherazade insisted on marrying the king, and actually wed him despite her father’s wise counsel to the contrary—when she insisted on the marriage, whether he liked it or not—she did so with her beautiful dark eyes as wide open as the circumstances permitted. It appears, however, that this clever young woman, who had surely studied Machiavelli, had devised a subtle scheme. On their wedding night, she arranged, under some plausible excuse, for her sister to sleep on a couch close enough to the royal bed to allow for easy conversation. Shortly before dawn, she managed to rouse the monarch, her husband—who held no grudge against her, even though he planned to break her neck the next day—by engaging him with the deep intrigue of a tale (concerning a rat and a black cat, I believe) which she was whispering to her sister. When morning arrived, the story remained incomplete, and Scheherazade naturally could not finish it then, as it was time for her to rise and be strangled—a fate slightly more refined than hanging, but hardly more pleasant. The king’s curiosity, however, unfortunately outweighed his religious convictions, leading him to delay his vow until the following morning, in the hope of learning how the black cat and the rat fared in the end."
}

