model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "POE_WORKS_VOLUME_2_006",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "I surely must have been feverish, as I even attempted to find diversion in guessing the comparative speeds at which various objects fell toward the churning spray beneath. I caught myself remarking that a particular pine tree would surely be the next to make the terrifying drop and vanish, yet I felt let down when the remains of a Dutch trading vessel passed it and sank first. Eventually, after making numerous such predictions and being wrong every time, this consistent failure to calculate correctly triggered a line of thought that caused my body to shake and my heart to pound violently once more.\n\nIt was not a fresh dread that troubled me, but rather the emergence of a more stimulating hope. This expectation stemmed partly from recollection and partly from what I was witnessing. I remembered the wide array of floating debris scattered along the Lofoden shore, which had been pulled into the Moskoe-ström and subsequently expelled. While the vast majority of these items were pulverized in a bizarre fashion—so worn and jagged that they looked as if they were embedded with slivers—I clearly recalled that some remained entirely undamaged. I could explain this discrepancy only by assuming that the battered pieces were the only ones fully pulled into the depths, while the others had either entered the vortex late in the tide cycle or descended so gradually that they failed to hit the bottom before the tide shifted. I reasoned that, in either scenario, they might be spun back up to the surface without suffering the same end as those drawn in sooner or swallowed more quickly. I also noted three significant points. First, larger objects generally descended faster. Second, between two items of equal size, the spherical one fell more quickly than any other shape. Third, between two items of equal size, the cylindrical one was pulled down more slowly. Since surviving, I have discussed this with a local schoolteacher, who provided the terms ‘cylinder’ and ‘sphere.’ He clarified—though I have lost the details—how my observations were the natural result of the shapes of the debris, demonstrating how a cylinder floating in a whirlpool resists suction more effectively than an object of equal volume in any other form.\n\nOne striking detail strongly reinforced these findings and made me eager to utilize them: with every rotation, we drifted past items like a barrel, a yardarm, or a ship’s mast, and many of these objects, which had been at our elevation when I first beheld the whirlpool’s marvels, were now far above us and appeared to have shifted very little from their initial position."
}

