model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "POE_WORKS_VOLUME_2_006",
  "condition": "modernize",
  "rewritten_text": "I must have been delirious, for I even tried to amuse myself by guessing the relative speeds at which various objects were falling toward the foam below. 'This fir tree,' I caught myself saying at one point, 'will surely be the next thing to take the terrifying plunge and vanish'—and then I was disappointed to see that the wreckage of a Dutch merchant ship overtook it and sank first. Eventually, after making several guesses of this kind and being wrong every time, this fact—the fact of my constant miscalculation—triggered a train of thought that made my limbs tremble again and my heart beat heavily once more.\n\nIt was not a new terror that affected me this way, but the dawn of a more exciting hope. This hope arose partly from memory and partly from current observation. I recalled the great variety of buoyant debris that littered the coast of Lofoden, having been pulled in and then spat out by the Moskoe-ström. By far the majority of these items were shattered in the most extraordinary way—so chafed and roughened that they appeared to be covered in splinters—but I distinctly remembered that there were some that were not disfigured at all. I could not explain this difference except by assuming that the roughened fragments were the only ones that had been completely absorbed—that the others had entered the whirlpool so late in the tide, or for some reason had descended so slowly after entering, that they did not reach the bottom before the tide turned. I thought it possible, in either case, that they might be whirled back up to the ocean's surface without suffering the fate of those that had been drawn in earlier or absorbed more rapidly. I also made three important observations. The first was that, as a general rule, the larger the objects were, the faster they descended; the second, that between two masses of equal size, one spherical and the other of any other shape, the sphere descended faster; the third, that between two masses of equal size, one cylindrical and the other of any other shape, the cylinder was absorbed more slowly. Since my escape, I have had several conversations on this subject with an old schoolteacher from the area, and it was from him that I learned the terms 'cylinder' and 'sphere.' He explained to me—though I have forgotten the explanation—how what I observed was, in fact, the natural consequence of the shapes of the floating fragments, and showed me how a cylinder, swimming in a vortex, offered more resistance to its suction and was drawn in with greater difficulty than an equally bulky body of any other shape.\n\nThere was one startling circumstance that went a long way toward reinforcing these observations and making me anxious to put them to use, which was that, with every revolution, we passed something like a barrel, or the yard or mast of a ship, while many of these things, which had been at our level when I first opened my eyes to the wonders of the whirlpool, were now high above us and seemed to have moved very little from their original position."
}

