  "rewritten_text": "I was destined for the latter. My nerves had been shattered by prolonged suffering, to the point where the sound of my own voice made me shudder, rendering me a perfect candidate for the torment that lay ahead. Trembling in every part of my body, I felt my way back to the wall, determined to die there rather than face the horrors of the pits, which my mind now envisioned scattered throughout the cell. In a different state of mind, I might have had the bravery to finish my agony by leaping into one of these chasms, but I was now a complete coward. Furthermore, I could not erase from my memory what I had read regarding these pits—that a quick death was never part of their most gruesome design. Mental distress kept me awake for many hours, but eventually, I drifted off again. Upon waking, I discovered a loaf of bread and a pitcher of water beside me, just as before. A fierce thirst overwhelmed me, and I drained the container in one gulp. It must have been spiked, for I grew uncontrollably sleepy almost immediately. A profound slumber overcame me, resembling death itself. I have no idea how long it endured, but when I opened my eyes again, the surroundings were discernible. A strange, sulfurous glow, the source of which I could not initially identify, allowed me to perceive the scale and appearance of the dungeon. I had been significantly wrong about its size. The entire perimeter of the walls was no more than twenty-five yards. For a few minutes, this realization caused me unnecessary distress; how futile! What could matter less, given the dire situation surrounding me, than the simple measurements of my cell? Yet my mind fixated on these trivialities, and I occupied myself trying to explain the mistake I had made in my estimation. The reality finally dawned on me. During my initial exploration, I had walked fifty-two paces before I fell; I must have been within a step or two of the piece of fabric, meaning I had nearly completed the circuit of the room. I then slept, and upon waking, I must have retraced my path, leading me to believe the circuit was nearly twice its actual length. My mental confusion kept me from noticing that I had started my journey with the wall on my left and finished with it on my right. I had also been misled regarding the shape of the space. While feeling my way, I had encountered numerous angles, leading me to conclude it was highly irregular; such is the power of total darkness on someone waking from a stupor! The angles were merely a few shallow indentations or niches at irregular intervals. The prison was essentially square. What I had perceived as stone masonry now appeared to be iron or some other metal, formed into massive plates whose seams created the depressions. The entire surface of this metallic enclosure was crudely painted with all the grotesque and unsettling imagery that monastic superstition regarding the grave has produced."
}

