 double its actual size. My confusion prevented me from noticing that I had started my tour with the wall on my left and ended it with the wall on my right. I had also been deceived regarding the shape of the enclosure. While feeling my way, I had found many angles and concluded that the room was very irregular; such is the power of total darkness on someone waking from a deep sleep! The angles were simply a few slight indentations or niches at odd intervals. The general shape of the prison was square. What I had taken for stone masonry now appeared to be iron or some other metal in huge plates, whose joints created the indentations. The entire surface of this metal enclosure was crudely painted with all the hideous and repulsive images that the death-obsessed superstitions of the monks had inspired."
