otential. The comments regarding identifying and utilizing subtle relations of size, proportion, and color represent one of those vague linguistic habits that merely mask imprecise thinking. The quoted statement could signify anything or nothing, and it provides no real direction. The claim that the true achievement of the natural style is found more in the omission of faults and contradictions than in the generation of unique wonders is a concept better suited to the limited understanding of the masses than to the passionate visions of a creative genius. The negative value proposed belongs to that timid school of criticism which, in literature, would deify Addison. In reality, while the virtue defined by the simple avoidance of wrongdoing speaks directly to the intellect and can therefore be defined by regulations, the higher virtue, which burns within the act of creation, can only be understood through its outcomes. Rules apply only to the merits of restraint—to the virtues of omission. Beyond these, critical theory can only offer suggestions. We might be taught how to construct a ‘Cato,’ but we are told in vain how to conceive a Parthenon or an ‘Inferno.’ Once the work is finished, however—the miracle achieved—the ability to appreciate it becomes widespread. The sophists of the negative school, who, lacking the power to create, have mocked the act of creation, are now the most vocal in their praise.”"
