Their dying light allowed us just enough time to perceive that a stranger had entered, about my own height, and closely muffled in a cloak. The darkness, however, was now total, and we could only sense that he was standing in our midst. Before any of us could recover from the extreme astonishment into which this rudeness had thrown us, we heard the voice of the intruder.\n\n“Gentlemen,” he said, in a low, distinct, and unforgettable whisper that chilled me to the bone, “Gentlemen, I offer no apology for this behavior, because in acting this way, I am merely fulfilling a duty. You are, without a doubt, unaware of the true character of the person who has tonight won a large sum of money from Lord Glendinning at écarté. I will therefore provide you with a quick and decisive way to obtain this very necessary information. Please examine, at your leisure, the inner linings of his left sleeve cuff, and the various little packages that may be found in the somewhat spacious pockets of his embroidered morning robe.”"
}

