  "rewritten_text": "Deeply aware of their obligations to the life they had created, and driven by a constant, affectionate spirit, my parents raised me with such gentle care that every lesson in patience, kindness, and restraint felt like a continuous stream of happiness. For a considerable time, I remained their sole focus. Although my mother had long hoped for a daughter, I stayed their only child. When I was five, during a trip outside Italy, they spent a week by Lake Como. Their generous nature frequently led them to visit the homes of the impoverished. For my mother, this was not merely an obligation but a profound necessity and passion; recalling her own past hardships and the aid she had received, she felt compelled to act as a protector for the suffering. On one excursion, a desolate cottage tucked away in a valley caught their attention, where the sight of several poorly dressed children revealed extreme destitution. One day, while my father was away in Milan, my mother took me to visit this dwelling. She discovered a hardworking peasant couple, worn down by labor and worry, sharing a meager meal with five hungry children. One child in particular captivated my mother. She seemed entirely different from the others. While the four siblings were dark-eyed and rugged, this girl was delicate and fair. Her hair shone like bright gold, and despite her ragged attire, it gave her an air of nobility. With a broad, clear forehead, serene blue eyes, and a face radiating sweetness and sensitivity, she appeared to be a creature of a higher order, marked by a heavenly grace. Observing my mother’s fascination, the peasant woman quickly shared the girl’s story. She was not their biological child, but the daughter of a Milanese nobleman and a German mother who had passed away during childbirth. The infant had been left with these kind people to be nursed when they were more prosperous and had only one child of their own. The girl’s father was a man devoted to the memory of Italy’s past greatness—one of those restless souls fighting for his country’s freedom—who eventually fell victim to its political instability. Whether he had perished or remained trapped in an Austrian prison was unknown. His assets were seized, leaving his daughter an orphan in poverty. She remained with her foster family, flourishing in their humble home like a garden rose amidst wild, dark brambles. Upon returning from Milan, my father discovered a child playing with me in our villa’s hall who was more beautiful than any painted angel—a being who seemed to glow with light, moving with a grace more agile than a mountain chamois."
}

