  "rewritten_text": "This thought cast me into a state of such hopeless terror that even now, as my life draws to its final close, I tremble to recall it. Several hours went by in this manner; yet as the sun sank toward the horizon, the wind faded into a soft breeze and the waves ceased their crashing. In their place came a heavy swell; I felt nauseated and barely capable of gripping the tiller, when all at once I spotted a stretch of high land to the south. Exhausted as I was by exhaustion and the agonizing uncertainty I had suffered for hours, this sudden promise of survival surged through me like a wave of warm relief, and tears poured from my eyes. How fickle our emotions are, and how peculiar is that desperate attachment we hold for life even when suffering intensely! I fashioned a makeshift sail from a piece of my clothing and steered my vessel toward the shore with great urgency. The terrain looked rugged and stony, but as I drew closer, I could clearly discern signs of human labor. I spotted ships near the coast and realized I had been brought back to the vicinity of civilized society. I followed the curves of the coastline and greeted a church spire that finally emerged from behind a small headland. Being in a state of profound weakness, I decided to steer straight for the town, where I could most readily obtain food. Luckily, I carried money. As I rounded the point, I saw a tidy little town with a fine harbor, which I entered, my heart leaping with delight at my unforeseen deliverance. While I was busy securing the boat and folding the sails, a group of people gathered nearby. They appeared quite startled by my condition, yet rather than helping, they muttered among themselves with motions that might have frightened me under different circumstances. As it was, I simply noted they were speaking English, so I spoke to them in that tongue. “Kind friends,” I asked, “would you be so good as to tell me the name of this town and where I have landed?” “You’ll find out soon enough,” a man with a gravelly voice answered. “Perhaps you’ve arrived at a place not much to your liking, but I assure you, you won’t be asked for your opinion on your accommodations.” I was deeply shocked by such a harsh reply from a stranger, and I felt unsettled by the scowling, hostile expressions of his peers. “Why do you speak so sharply?” I asked. “Surely it is not the habit of the English to treat travelers with such lack of hospitality.” “I cannot say,” the man replied, “what the English custom may be, but it is the Irish custom to despise scoundrels.” As this odd exchange went on, I noticed the crowd growing quickly. Their faces showed a blend of inquisitiveness and hostility, which bothered and somewhat frightened me. I asked for directions to the inn, but nobody answered. I then began to walk, and a low murmur rose from the throng as they trailed and encircled me, until a sinister-looking man stepped forward, touched my shoulder, and said, “Come, sir, you must accompany me to Mr."
}

