  "rewritten_text": "The meeting hall stood empty, and the throngs of people who once served as instruments for his many schemes were now ignored. Revelry, and even debauchery, became the standard practice. Perdita watched the growing chaos with alarm. For an instant, she believed she might hold back the tide and persuade Raymond to listen to her logic. It was a futile wish. Her time of influence had vanished. He heard her with arrogance and answered with scorn; if she managed to stir his conscience, the only result was that he looked for a way to numb the pain through mindless excess. With her characteristic vigor, Perdita then tried to fill his role. Their marriage, still outwardly intact, allowed her to accomplish a great deal, yet no woman could ultimately fix the Protector’s mounting neglect. He acted as if gripped by a fit of madness, disregarding all decorum, structure, and responsibility, surrendering himself entirely to indulgence. News of these bizarre events came to us, and we were unsure how to proceed to bring our friend back to his senses and his nation, when Perdita unexpectedly arrived. She described the development of this tragic transformation and begged Adrian and me to travel to London to try and curb the worsening situation. Tell him, she exclaimed, tell Lord Raymond that I will no longer bother him with my presence. He does not need to throw himself into this ruinous debauchery to repel me or force me to leave. That goal is now met; he shall never see me again. But let me, as my final request, find in the acclaim of his fellow citizens and the success of England that the choice of my youth was correct. While riding to the city, Adrian and I debated Raymond’s behavior and his failure to live up to the promise of lasting greatness he had previously shown us. My companion and I had been raised with the same belief, or rather, I was his student in the conviction that unwavering commitment to principle was the sole path to glory, and that a constant focus on the common good was the only honorable goal for human ambition. Although we shared these views, we disagreed on how to apply them. Anger sharpened my criticism, and I condemned Raymond’s actions harshly. Adrian was more gentle and thoughtful. He acknowledged that my principles were ideal, but he rejected the idea that they were the only ones. Referencing the scripture that there are many mansions in my father’s house, he argued that the ways to achieve goodness or greatness are as varied as the temperaments of men, of whom it could be said, as of the leaves in the woods, that no two are identical. We reached London around eleven in the evening. We assumed, despite what we had been told, that we would locate Raymond at St. Stephen’s, so we hurried there. The hall was crowded, but the Protector was absent; a stern dissatisfaction was visible on the faces of the officials, and there was a restless, ominous murmuring among the subordinates. We rushed to the Protector’s palace. We discovered Raymond in his dining chamber with six companions; the wine was circulating freely, and it had already significantly clouded the judgment of one or two of them."
}

