  "passage_id": "SHELLEY_THE_LAST_MAN_015",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "An unusual report reached us from the East, which might have been dismissed as unbelievable had it not been confirmed by numerous observers across various regions of the globe. It was claimed that on the twenty-first of June, an hour before midday, a black sun appeared. This orb, matching the size of the true sun but dark and distinct, with rays composed of shadow, rose from the west. Within an hour, it reached the zenith and obscured the radiant source of daylight. Darkness descended upon every land—a sudden, absolute, and lightless night. Stars emerged, casting their feeble glow upon the earth, now bereft of its sun. Before long, however, the gloomy sphere moved away from the sun and drifted toward the eastern sky. As it descended, its murky beams intersected with the brilliant rays of the sun, muting or warping them. The shadows cast by objects took on bizarre and terrifying forms. Wild creatures in the forests were startled by the unfamiliar shapes projected onto the ground. They fled in aimless terror, while the populace was gripped by even greater alarm at the upheaval that drove lions into populated streets. Powerful eagles, suddenly struck blind, plummeted into marketplaces, while owls and bats emerged to greet the premature night. Eventually, this object of terror dipped below the horizon, casting shadowy rays into the otherwise bright atmosphere until the very end. This was the account relayed from Asia, the eastern reaches of Europe, and Africa as far west as the Gold Coast. Regardless of the story's veracity, its consequences were undeniable. Throughout Asia, from the Nile's banks to the Caspian shores, and from the Hellespont to the Sea of Oman, a sudden terror took hold. Men crowded into mosques, while veiled women hurried to gravesites, bringing gifts for the departed in hopes of safeguarding the living. The plague was eclipsed by this new dread ignited by the black sun; even as the death toll rose and the streets of Ispahan, Pekin, and Delhi were littered with victims of the pestilence, people walked past, staring at the ominous heavens, indifferent to the corpses beneath them. Christians flocked to their churches; young Christian women, even during the festival of roses, dressed in white with shimmering veils, moved in lengthy processions toward their sacred sites, filling the air with hymns. Occasionally, a cry of lamentation would erupt from a grieving soul in the throng, causing others to look upward, imagining they could see the sweeping wings of angels passing over the world, mourning the calamities destined to befall humanity.\n\nIn the sun-drenched regions of Persia, the densely populated cities of China, the fragrant groves of Cashmere, and along the southern Mediterranean coast, such events transpired. Even in Greece, the legend of the dark sun intensified the anxiety and hopelessness of the perishing masses. We, situated on our misty island, were distant from the peril, and the only factor that made these catastrophes feel relevant to us was the constant arrival of ships from the east, packed with refugees, primarily English. The Muslims, though deeply affected by the fear of death, remained united; they reasoned that if they were destined to perish—and death would find them just as easily on the desolate ocean or in distant England as it would in Persia—they preferred that their remains rest in soil sanctified by the relics of the faithful."
}

