o debauchery to escape the painful pangs of extreme dread. Thus, while the virtuous, wise, and careful were engaged in charitable work, the winter lull created different results among the young, the reckless, and the immoral. Throughout the colder months, there was a widespread migration to London seeking entertainment; social constraints weakened; many who were previously poor had become wealthy; many had lost the parents who served as their moral guardians and guides. It would have been futile to resist these urges with obstacles, which would only have pushed those driven by them toward more harmful excesses. The theaters remained open and crowded; dances and late-night celebrations were popular—in many of these, propriety was abandoned, and the vices previously associated with a sophisticated society were magnified. The scholar abandoned his texts, the artist his studio: life’s serious pursuits had vanished, but the diversions persisted; pleasure could be extended to the very edge of the grave. All artificial pretenses vanished—death ascended like the night, and, shielded by its dark shadows, the blush of modesty, the reserve of pride, and the decorum of prudery were often discarded as pointless masks. This was not the case everywhere. Among nobler souls, suffering and terror, the dread of permanent separation, and the profound astonishment caused by this unprecedented disaster, tightened the bonds of family and friendship."
}

