model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "SHELLEY_THE_LAST_MAN_021",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "The bustling eastern district of the city remained quiet, or revealed only spots where warehouses had been rummaged through, driven by greed or inquisitiveness: bundles of expensive Indian merchandise, costly shawls, gems, and spices lay scattered across the ground. In certain spots, the owner had guarded their inventory until the end, perishing in front of locked entrances. The heavy church doors groaned on their hinges, with a few corpses resting upon the stone floors. A miserable woman, the unloved casualty of common violence, had drifted into the dressing room of an aristocrat, draped herself in fine clothing, and expired before the glass that showed her transformed reflection. Ladies whose soft feet had rarely trod the ground in their pampered lives had escaped their residences in terror, only to become lost in the city's grimy lanes and perish at the doors of the destitute. My heart grew weary at the diverse miseries on display; witnessing such grim transformations, my spirit was pained by the dread of what might happen to my dear Idris and our children. Would they, outliving Adrian and me, be left without guardians in this world? Thus far, only the mind had been tormented—could I indefinitely delay the moment when the fragile body and sensitive nerves of my beloved, raised in luxury and rank, would be assaulted by starvation, suffering, and sickness? It would be better to perish immediately—better to drive a dagger into her chest, still unmarred by harsh misfortune, and then bury it in my own! Yet, no; during eras of suffering, we must battle our fates and endeavor not to be conquered by them. I refused to surrender, determined to shield my loved ones from grief and agony until my final breath; if I were eventually defeated, it would not be without honor. I remained at the barricade, opposing the adversary—the intangible, unseen enemy that had besieged us for so long—and as of yet, he had created no opening: it had to be my duty to ensure he did not, by burrowing in secret, erupt within the very sanctuary of love where I offered my daily devotions. The appetite of Death seemed sharpened by the dwindling supply of his victims: or perhaps it was simply that before, when survivors were numerous, the dead were tallied with less urgency? Now, every life was a treasure, every breathing human being worth far more than the finest carved statues; and the daily, indeed hourly, decline in our population struck the heart with nauseating despair. This summer saw our hopes extinguished; the ship of civilization was destroyed, and the broken raft, bearing the remaining few across a sea of sorrow, was split and battered by storms. Humanity existed only in pairs or trios; the individual human, who might slumber, wake, and carry out basic biological needs, remained; but humanity, inherently fragile yet mightier in collective groups than the wind or the sea; humanity, the conqueror of nature, the master of creation, the equal of deities, existed no more. Farewell to the scenes of patriotism, to the devotion to freedom and the deserved rewards of noble ambition!—farewell to the packed parliament, resonant with the wisdom of counselors, whose decrees were sharper than a blade forged in Damascus!"
}

