ne us and burst into the very sanctuary of the love I served daily. Death’s hunger seemed sharper now as his food supply dwindled; or perhaps it was simply that when there were more survivors, the dead were counted less eagerly. Now, every life was a gem, every breathing human being worth far more than the finest sculpture; the daily, even hourly, decline in our numbers struck the heart with sickening misery. This summer extinguished our hopes; the vessel of society was wrecked, and the shattered raft carrying the few survivors across the sea of misery was torn apart by the storm. Humanity existed only in twos and threes; the individual might still sleep, wake, and function, but man—once weak alone yet more powerful in groups than the wind or ocean, the conqueror of the elements, the lord of nature, the equal of gods—existed no longer. Farewell to the patriotic scene, to the love of liberty, and to the well-earned rewards of virtuous ambition! Farewell to the crowded senate, echoing with the advice of the wise, whose laws were sharper than a Damascus blade!"
