  "passage_id": "SHELLEY_THE_LAST_MAN_023",
  "condition": "simplify",
  "rewritten_text": "Her courage only faltered when she feared danger for her parent, or worried that death might stop her from fulfilling the duties to which she was completely devoted. When we left Windsor for London, as the first step toward our final departure, we visited Lucy and organized the plan for her and her mother’s relocation. Lucy was saddened by the necessity of leaving her native lanes and village, and by having to move an infirm parent from the comforts of home into the empty, desolate world. However, she had been so well trained by hardship, and possessed such a sweet temperament, that she did not complain about what was unavoidable. Later events, including my illness and that of Idris, pushed her from our thoughts. We only remembered her eventually, assuming she was among the few who had traveled from Windsor to join the emigrants and was already in Paris. Therefore, when we arrived at Rochester, we were surprised to receive a letter from this exemplary woman, delivered by a man who had just come from Slough. He explained that while traveling from his home through Datchet, he was surprised to see smoke coming from the inn’s chimney. Thinking he might find companions for his journey, he knocked and was let in. There was no one in the house but Lucy and her mother. The mother had lost the use of her limbs due to a severe case of rheumatism, and one by one, all the remaining local residents had left, abandoning them. Lucy begged the man to stay with her, promising that her mother would be better in a week or two and they could then set out, but she insisted they would surely perish if left so helpless and alone. The man replied that his wife and children were already among the emigrants, so he felt it was impossible for him to stay. As a final resort, Lucy gave him a letter for Idris, to be delivered wherever he might find us. He fulfilled this request, and Idris was moved to receive the following letter: “Honoured Lady, I am sure you will remember and pity me, and I dare hope you will assist me; what other hope do I have? Please pardon my writing, as I am so bewildered. A month ago, my dear mother lost the use of her limbs. She is already improving, and I am certain that in another month she would be able to travel in the way you kindly offered to arrange for us. But now everyone is gone—everyone. As they left, they each said that perhaps my mother would be better before we were completely deserted. Three days ago, I went to Samuel Woods, who had stayed until the end because of his newborn child. Since they were a large family, I thought I could persuade them to wait a little longer for us, but I found their house empty. I have not seen a soul since, until this good man arrived. What will become of us? My mother does not know our situation; she is so ill that I have kept it hidden from her.”"
}

