model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "SHELLEY_THE_LAST_MAN_027",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "We had anticipated this juncture with intensity, as the most arduous segment of our bleak trek was finished, and Switzerland lay ahead. Still, how could we celebrate a triumph so incomplete? Were these forlorn creatures, trudging by in mournful lines, the final survivors of a human race that once, like a deluge, covered and claimed the entire globe? It had flowed pure and unobstructed from its original mountain spring at Ararat, expanding from a tiny brook into a massive, constant river, with generations pouring forth without end. Consistent yet varied, it surged toward the consuming sea, whose hazy banks we now approached. Humanity was merely nature’s toy when it first emerged from the empty void into the light; yet intellect birthed power and wisdom, and, adorned with these, mankind claimed stature and command. It was no longer just the earth’s gardener or a shepherd of flocks; it possessed a grand and stately presence, boasting a lineage, noble forebears, a collection of portraits, carved memorials, and documented titles.\n\nAll of this had vanished, now that the sea of death had swallowed the waning tide and its fountainhead had withered. We had initially said goodbye to the order of existence that, having endured for millennia, seemed permanent—that structure of governance, submission, commerce, and social life that had shaped our spirits and abilities for as long as we could remember. Then, we bid farewell to national fervor, the arts, prestige, lasting renown, and the very concept of a homeland. We watched every hope of reclaiming our former state depart—every expectation, save for the faint desire to rescue our own lives from the ruins of the past. To save them, we had abandoned England—England, no more; for without its people, what title could that desolate isle hold? We held tightly to whatever governance and discipline might best protect us, hoping that if a small settlement could survive, it might eventually suffice to revive the lost fellowship of humanity.\n\nBut the end has arrived! We are all destined to die, leaving neither survivor nor successor to the vast legacy of the world. We must all perish! The human species must vanish; its frame of delicate craftsmanship; the miraculous apparatus of its senses; the magnificent symmetry of its divine limbs; its mind, the enthroned ruler of these; all must cease. Will the earth maintain its position among the stars; will it continue its steady orbit around the sun; will the seasons shift, the trees dress themselves in foliage, and blossoms release their scent, all in isolation? Will the peaks stand firm, and rivers continue their descent toward the great deep; will the tides ebb and flow, and breezes stir the natural world; will animals graze, birds soar, and fish glide, once man, the master, owner, observer, and chronicler of all these wonders, has vanished as if he had never existed? Oh, what a cruel irony! Surely death is not truly death, and humanity is not gone, but has simply transformed into other forms, beyond the reach of our senses."
}

