g desperately to whatever rules and order could best protect us, trusting that if a small colony could be saved, it would eventually be enough to restore the lost community of mankind.\n\nBut the game is over! We must all die, leaving neither survivor nor heir to the vast inheritance of the earth. We must all die! The human species must perish; its exquisitely crafted frame, the wondrous mechanism of its senses, the noble proportions of its godlike limbs, and its mind, the enthroned king of all these, must perish. Will the earth still keep its place among the planets; will it still travel with silent regularity around the sun; will the seasons change, the trees dress themselves in leaves, and flowers release their fragrance in solitude? Will the mountains remain unmoved, and streams still flow downward toward the vast abyss; will the tides rise and fall, and the winds blow across the natural world; will beasts graze, birds fly, and fish swim, when man, the lord, possessor, observer, and recorder of all these things, has vanished as if he had never existed? Oh, what a mockery this is! Surely death is not truly death, and humanity is not extinct, but has merely transformed into other shapes, beyond our ability to perceive."
