ity of mankind.\n\nBut the game is over! We must all die, leaving no survivors or heirs to inherit the earth. We must all die! The human species must perish; our bodies of exquisite workmanship, the wondrous mechanism of our senses, the noble proportions of our godlike limbs, and our minds—the throned kings of all these—must perish. Will the earth still keep its place among the planets? Will it still travel with steady regularity around the sun? Will the seasons change, the trees grow leaves, and the flowers shed their fragrance in solitude? Will the mountains remain unmoved, the streams continue their downward course toward the vast abyss, the tides rise and fall, and the winds blow through nature? Will beasts graze, birds fly, and fish swim when man—the lord, possessor, observer, and recorder of all these things—has passed away as if he had never existed? Oh, what a mockery this is! Surely death is not truly the end, and humanity is not extinct, but has merely passed into other forms that we can no longer perceive."
}

