  "rewritten_text": "Shall it come to pass? We were accustomed to anticipate death with trembling, yet was that not simply because its destination remained hidden? Far more frightening, and significantly more veiled, was the revealed path of my solitary future. I snapped my staff and cast it aside. I required no instrument to measure the incremental progress of my existence, as my restless mind forged divisions far different from those governed by the stars. Reflecting upon the era that had passed since I became solitary, I refused to label the spasms of suffering that truly defined it as mere days or hours.\n\nI covered my countenance with my palms. The chirping of fledgling birds settling for the night and their movement within the branches disrupted the quiet evening air; crickets sang, and the aziolo called out periodically. My reflections had centered on death, yet these noises whispered of life. I raised my gaze; a bat circled overhead. The sun had descended behind the serrated mountain peaks, and the pale, crescent moon appeared, silvery and bright against the amber sunset, joined by a single radiant star that extended the twilight. A group of cattle wandered through the valley below, unguided, toward their watering hole. The breeze stirred the grass, and the olive groves, softened into gentle shapes by the moonlight, set their sea-green hues against the deep chestnut leaves. Indeed, this remains the earth; there is no alteration, no destruction, no tear within her lush surface. She persists in her rotation, alternating between night and day across the heavens, even though humanity no longer inhabits or beautifies her. Why could I not lose myself as those creatures do, and cease to endure the frantic turmoil of my agony? Yet, alas, what a fatal chasm separates their condition from my own! Do they not possess companions? Do they not each have a mate, their beloved offspring, and a home that, while unspoken to us, is surely cherished and enriched in their perception by the community nature has provided? I alone am solitary; I, upon this small summit, observing the plains and mountain hollows, the sky and its celestial inhabitants, listening to every vibration of the earth, the atmosphere, and the whispering tide. I alone cannot share my numerous thoughts with a companion, nor rest my aching head upon a beloved breast, nor draw from meeting eyes a divine essence that surpasses the legendary nectar of the deities. Shall I not then lament? Shall I not denounce the lethal mechanism that has harvested the children of men, my kin? Shall I not cast a curse upon every other creature of nature that dares to exist and find pleasure, while I remain to live and suffer?\n\nOh, no! I shall train my grieving heart to share in your delights; I will find happiness because you possess it. Continue to exist, you innocent ones, the favored children of nature; I am not so different from you. My being is formed of nerves, pulse, brain, joints, and flesh, and you are structured by those same principles. I possess something beyond this, yet I shall label it a flaw rather than a gift if it leads me to despair while you remain content. At that moment, two goats and a small kid emerged from a nearby thicket, staying close to the mother, and began to graze upon the hill's vegetation."
}

